Rating: 4
I read a lot of the reviews before making this recipe for the first time. First can I just say "pudding" is an old world term often used to describe "dessert". Don't think of this as your average American cooked custard "pudding" dessert (e.g., Jell-o Pudding). That's not what this is, it's closer to a buckle and should be a cross between cake and fruit compote. Secondly, I made this for my hubby the first time according to the recipe, but did incorporate the advice of others (especially that about the salt) on this site. It was fab-o and he loved it. This is important because he's not a very big blueberry fan. The second time I made it, I used rhubarb (more to hubby's liking). It still turned out great, but needs a few modifications to be the same steller recipe of the original. I added to the ruhubarb some traditional spices (nutmeg, star anise, cinnamon) and used brown sugar instead of white in the fruit component only. As I said, I need to figure out the ratio (too much rhubarb to cake). I will do this by making the blueberry version again and measuring the blueberry syrup before adding it to the cake. However, if anyone has ideas on the amount of syrup to cake, I'd love to hear them. Bottom line, I'm adding this recipe to my summer/fall recipe collection. Give it a try, you won't regret it!

